The Higgs boson analyzed
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson has attracted a certain stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is indeed believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But it is not yet completely certain for the physicists that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still lacking data to be completely safe.
Nevertheless, let us assume that it is actually the Higgs, since there is apparently only a small risk of deceiving oneself, and let us look at what it is at stake.
There is an inevitably unavoidable law in this world, which causes two objects to not be present at the same time at the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too much, as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to them: Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state", largely this "state" consists of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called fathers and who obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons, an evil gang of anarchists, who are not sacred to anything - definitely not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely surprising): the mesons, which we will not treat here and the "power particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
It must be stressed here, however, that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bot" of electromagnetic force.
If a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this location, such as a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the bosons "barriers of force".
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disordered" for this boson to show itself.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be ragged by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, there are not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep the fridge by itself.
And not all particles interact with the Higgs field equally: those who do have one mass, while the others (as they like the photon, by the way) have no mass.
What can all these research be "good" for, asks Ms Plamondon?
For science, they serve to verify the Standard Model (SM), and they also allow physicists to investigate all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM closely.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who most earnestly hope that such deviations will be found, since the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stuff some holes in the model.
It has to be said that the latter still has great defects, since it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter, which approx. 80% of the matter of the universe forms (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN until now.
Impact
The effects of this research on the general population are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be none.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous profile laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - has already told us that the laser was regarded at the beginning rather as a "laboratory playing."
Imagine yourself...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
