Several thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After Bitcoin's peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell to 2 dollars five months later, before recovering to around ten dollars today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currency or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to traditional currencies".
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies such as the "credits" used to move forward in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes exchange back) by playing games.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trading is controlled and processed by a central authority each time.
With Bitcoin, all net nodes are simultaneously depositors of the account book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
With the help of the file's content, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are available in the public account invoice book distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of preliminary central banker, has the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money twice as many times (less than 10 minutes) for cheating, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain without a link, since both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to a hundred millionth of a time, leaving a certain amount of leeway...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying for real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering with the help of this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these defects.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the account book and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, a "mega-close sale" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts Bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions, which are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented at retailers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You simply need to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, gives Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are reconsidered in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but in 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
Incidentally, the ECB envisages in its report of reassessing the various risks that are considered high today in the event of a success of this currency.
