It is a new poker game by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever regarding the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants its unlimited power, he has decided to put everything on one card.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just one week ago, the head of state had granted this plenum two additional months to complete his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has relied on a preliminary, several times as amended, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has caused only an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trail the right feet".
His supporters assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum was to be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to renounce their plan to declare the text section for section to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to rediscover its public and democratic legitimacy, while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After affirmation in an interview with the American newsreel Time, Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will be sympathetic to vote.
Especially since the Egyptian people are ultimatum with this recourse to a hasty vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I keep the unlimited authority", the latter supposedly shall put an end to the constitution once the constitution is now said.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals did not comply with the request.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they were unable to bring their views to bear.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities and civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 persons, alternate members, were added yesterday morning in a hurry.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, since some members of the body were of the opinion that the pendulum clock of the constituent assembly was not exactly possible.
The text, which was adopted yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, eventually remains identical with that of the Constitution of 1971, saying that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
