Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants could be falsified.
Some fake certificates, which certify the language test, have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive these for nothing: every migrant who hoped to spare such tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Both officials and civil rights professionals agree that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased.
For now, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test the first time that they will receive time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered where no active communication with people is required.
