In November 1979, a mob demonstrating Islamist students occupied the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah's Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the USA after the revolution, which had maintained the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the American government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was not able to impose the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free the hostage made everything even worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations were arranged by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home caused a wave of solidarity and anti-iriatan sentiment.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story, which gave the USA a small victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian Ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, succeeded in bringing the refugees from Iran, helping them to reveal an extravagant story to cover their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff that allegedly visited shooting locations for a science fiction film in the country.
Combination of genres
The plan, developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood collaboration.
In order for the camouflage to become credible, articles about this film project appeared in journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand it is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time a so-called one. "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the levels of mood alternate in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no big differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood come along ironicly and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the corridors, on the telephone...
With this film, Ben Affleck has managed a remarkable restart of his career.
A ridiculed actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film after the Crime No Child's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (USA (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film that does not play in the director's native Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that took off the director's previous films from Hollywood's standard.
However, Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film are set in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the opening sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and yet conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story comes somewhere.
Affleck and his team also achieve a similar effect in fictitious scenes (the wrong movie staff on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story doesn't actually offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
However, he works quite successfully with whatever number, whereby he sometimes helps reality somewhat - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem a little artificial).
The weakness of Argo is his all too broad dispersion, which is conditioned by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters have earned more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film loses some of its traction. It's a film you follow with some interest and the design and the thriller from the 70. years of reminiscent retro style can be emitting.
