I grew up in Central California and was called a "Mexicon" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Ir" or my friends in New York "Italians".
Later I chose "Mexicon-American".
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don't have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won't get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and lined up for Extranjeros.
I was thinking about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet President Obama.
The agenda included all those issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trafficking.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy. It is one reason why Mexicans are equally likely to remain in Mexico today, rather than emigrating to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue Mexico’s war against the drug cartels, even if he did not give any details in this respect.
Mexico's relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country to hold a rifle to leave more than half of its territory to them.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. official even makes the most lenient criticism of Mexico, one hears complaints about how the Americans are begging the sovereignty of their neighbouring country in the Mexican press and among the elites.
And the children of Montezuma go on the warpath.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge is in reality in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican origin live in cities such as Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our pedigree, a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - was not offered a chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is for them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now live the American dream, visit good schools and have received good jobs, we must never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity is sometimes blurred, but what concerns our loyalty is not the case.
This is clearly the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have gone.
And then we wouldn't see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans, because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans are taking this hold.
