But many Mexican Americans I know feel that they are not part of either, one, the country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but there is no rooted in any of them.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational middle class want to resume their ties with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, who represent their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well.
That will not happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unjust distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure whether it is really a great country.
I fear that you have to go through alone, Amigos.
That is fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet ready to award the United States to deal with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a resentment of how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we are "Mexicon" when I thought.
