The world's first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia. This replaces brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic pictures, which show sick body parts and infants and children who are suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small fonts, is after coming Saturday.
Australia is thus introducing the world's strictest regulations for tobacco packaging.
The Australian Government wants to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous picture of tobacco use.
The government is based on studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 will not start with 99% probability even afterwards.
"You can already see young age among children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She cites studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have only a minor impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the law.
It was said that the laws would favour the black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the roads of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha from Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that the demand for cigarette cases and silicone covers to cover the unbearable packaging has increased enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed two months ago on the Supreme Court of Australia with their contestation of the law.
